         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25/4/88. ¶  ¶ This day, dear Sir Joseph, a trading horticulturist here sent me a flowering Dendrobium Sumneri, which gave me an opportunity of verifying the original description from a fresh living pl...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">88.04.25</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, ff. 248-9.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">25/4/88.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">MS is stamped:</seg> Royal Gardens Kew 4-Jun. 88.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This day, dear Sir Joseph, a trading horticulturist here sent me a flowering <name key="Dendrobium%20Sumneri">Dendrobium Sumneri</name>, which gave me an opportunity of verifying the original description from a fresh living plant, and at the same time to settle, that your suspicion of D. Phalaenopsis being identical with D. Sumneri, was well founded. Indeed the two cannot even be separated as varieties. What you caused to be depicted in the bot. Magazine 6817<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker (1865–1904), vol. 111, t. 6817.</p>
               </note> is merely somewhat larger, though perhaps through cultured luxuriancy.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Will you kindly let Prof Dyer know this, so that the first name for this plant may be given to it also in the Kew Orchid House. Since I left the Garden I have very rarely opportunities to extend my researches to cultivated ornamental plants.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I had a kind letter from you last week,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker to M, 4 March 1888.</p>
               </note> concerning the labor involved in rearranging the genera of many great orders, an achievement, <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">I</hi>
               </seg> know to appreciate. Indeed if you never had done anything else than writing your share of the "genera",<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> it would immortalize you! Remarkably enough, intervals of about 40 years were between all the great "genera plantarum", which Tournefort, Linnaeus, Jussieu, Endlicher and finally you and Bentham wrote. It is now nearly 30 years since you took up the genera. I am sure we all wish, you could crown your labours with a new edition of that great opus, embracing all the discoveries of the three last decades. — You allude kindly to the Royal Society having had brought under its cognizance, what I may have accomplished here; all I can say is, that I honestly <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">did</hi>
               </seg> what I <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">could</hi>
               </seg> in a new distant land, and as I have <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">neither</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">property</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">nor family,</hi>
               </seg> I should regard any recognition from the great Royal Society now so late in my life all the more.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See also M to P. Sclater, December 1887. M was awarded one of the Royal Society's two Royal Medals for 1888.</p>
               </note> this is the first centennial Jubilee year for Australia too!<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. the centenary of British settlement in Australia: ‘this is … Australia too!’ is a marginal note with the intended position indicated by an asterisk.</p>
               </note> Lady Hooker sent me kindly an impression of your admirable speech given on the occasion, when you received the Societys <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">highest</hi>
               </seg> bestowal.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker received the Royal Society's Copley Medal at the Society's Anniversary Meeting on 30 November 1887.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Perhaps you and Lady Hooker will at the end of the summer be down in some part of the coast, and her Ladyship may help you to look for Cheno[le]a Hirsuta. As I found it on the Schleswig coast, nearly half a century ago, directly opposite the British, [often] in a glabrous form among Suaeda, you are sure to discover it also there, though the W. coast may be still more promising for finding it.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The postscripts are written in the side and central margins of the letter.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Mr Fitzgerald illustrated D. Smillieae &amp; <name key="Sarcochilus%20Hartmanni">Sarcochilus Hartmanni</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>S. hartmannii?</p>
               </note> also under new names, though well known in cultivation.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">D. Smillieae</seg> as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Coelandria smillieae</seg> (R. Fitzgerald (1875-94), vol .1 part 7, plate [2]), and described<seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Sarcochilus%20Hartmanni">Sarcochilus Hartmanni</name>
                     </seg> as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Sarcochilus rubricentrum </seg>(R. Fitzgerald (1880)) and illustrated it in R. Fitzgerald (1875-94), vol. 2, plate [3].</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When the "Key"<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B88.11.02.</p>
               </note> shall be through the press, I shall come to the naming of Papuan plants again, and then make up a set for Kew.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Towards autumn the sometimes spiral twist of the Chenolea is most marked; the axillary minute tufts of hairs lead also to distinguishing it from <name key="Suaeda%20maritima">Suaeda maritima</name>, &amp; of course the fruit altho' minute</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Chenolea%20Hirsuta">Chenolea Hirsuta</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dendrobium%20Phalaenopsis">Dendrobium Phalaenopsis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dendrobium%20Smillieae">Dendrobium Smillieae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Dendrobium%20Sumneri">Dendrobium Sumneri</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Sarcochilus%20Hartmanni">Sarcochilus Hartmanni</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Suaeda%20maritima">Suaeda maritima</name>
            </p>
         </div>
